"The sea is ours": Bolivia, a landlocked country, hopes that the court will restore a path to the Pacific
Sailors patrol a rope-covered naval base in La Paz.
Public buildings carry a navy blue flag.
The naval bases of Lake Titicaca for the Amazon bear the motto: “The sea is ours by right.
Retrieving it is a duty.”
Across landlocked Bolivia, the memory of a lost coastline to Chile in a bloody resource conflict in the 19th century is still alive, as is the longing to sail once again in the Pacific Ocean.
These hopes are perhaps at the highest point in decades, as Bolivia awaits a ruling by the International Court of Justice on October 1, after five years of deliberations.
“Bolivia has the momentum, a spirit of unity and serenity and, of course, a positive outlook on the outcome,” said Roberto Calzadilla, a Bolivian diplomat.
Many Bolivians will watch the TIJ’s sentencing on giant screens across the country, hoping that the court in The Hague will rule in favor of their country’s claim, so that after decades of uncertain negotiations, Chile will be forced to negotiate, granting Bolivia a sovereign exit into the sea.
Evo Morales, the charismatic indigenous Bolivian president facing a controversial re-election battle next year, also has a lot at stake in Monday’s ruling.
"We are very close to returning to the Pacific Ocean," the president said in August.
However, some analysts believe it is unlikely that the court will rule in favor of Bolivia, and that little would change even if not.
The United Nations body, based in the Netherlands, has no power to assign Chilean territory to another country and has stipulated that it will not determine the outcome of possible negotiations.
That the IJC’s sentence was handed down just six months after the hearing of the final allegations indicates that the case “was not complicated,” said Paz Zárate, a Chilean expert on international law.
And far from promoting the Bolivian cause, the last four years may have harmed it.
“The issue of access to the sea has been hijacked by the current Bolivian administration,” Zárate said.
Morales' belligerent rhetoric undermined some residual Chilean goodwill, he suggested.
At some point in the future, Bolivia and Chile will continue the talks, but it will be extremely difficult to maintain the dialogue after that.
The two countries have not exchanged ambassadors since 1962.
Former President Eduardo Rodríguez Veltzé, Bolivia’s representative in The Hague, rejected the idea that the court’s decision process was unusually fast.
Next Monday will give Bolivia “an extraordinary opportunity to usher in a new era of relations with Chile” and a chance to “end 139 years of disagreements with mutual benefits,” he said.
Calzadilla also denied that Morales, still one of Latin America’s most popular presidents, was using the maritime issue as a political crutch.
“Bolivia will never give up its right of access to the Pacific Ocean,” he added.
“The sentence is an opportunity to understand that we have to go beyond the past.”
