North Korea says 'never think' of unilateral disarmament without confidence
North Korea's foreign minister told the United Nations on Saturday that continued sanctions were aggravating distrust of the United States and that there was no way the country could unilaterally dispense with its nuclear weapons under those circumstances.
Ri Yong Ho told the World Assembly that North Korea had taken “significant goodwill measures” last year, such as halting nuclear and missile tests, dismantling the nuclear test center, and committing to non-proliferation of nuclear weapons and technologies.
"However, we do not see any corresponding U.S. response," he said.
“Without trust in the United States there will be no confidence in our national security and in such circumstances there is no way we can proceed to our disarmament first.”
Although Ri has recycled already-known North Korean complaints about Washington’s resistance to a “phased” approach to denuclearization, under which North Korea would be rewarded as it made gradual steps, his statements appear to be significant in that they do not limynarily reject unilateral denuclearization, in contrast to Pyongyang’s previous positions.
Ri referred to a joint statement issued by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump at the first ever summit between a sitting U.S. president and a North Korean leader in Singapore on June 12, where Kim pledged to work toward “denuclearization of the Korean peninsula,” while Trump offered security guarantees to North Korea.
North Korea has sought a formal end to the 1950-53 Korean war, but the United States claims that Pyongyang must first abandon its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also resisted calls to ease tough international sanctions against North Korea.
“The United States insists on “denuclearization first” and raises the level of pressure with sanctions to reach its goal coercively, opposing even the “declaration of the end of the war,” Ri said.
“The perception that sanctions can bring us to our knees is an impossible dream of people who know nothing about us.
However, the problem is that prolonging sanctions is compounding our mistrust.”
Ri did not mention plans for the second summit between Kim and Trump that had been referred to by the U.S. leader at the United Nations earlier this week.
Instead, the minister highlighted the three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in in the past five months, adding: “If the stakeholder in this issue were South Korea and not the US, the denuclearization of the Korean peninsula would not have reached this impasse.”
Still, the tone of Ri’s speech was drastically different from last year when he told the U.N. General Assembly that steering North Korea’s rockets toward U.S. territory was inevitable after “Mr. Bad President” Trump called Kim the “rocket man” on a suicide mission.
This year at the United Nations, Trump, who last year threatened to "completely destroy" North Korea, praised Kim for his courage to take steps toward disarmament, but said much remained to be done and sanctions would have to continue until North Korea's denuclearization.
On Wednesday, Trump said he did not have a timetable for it, saying “whether it takes two years, three years or five months, it doesn’t matter.”
China and Russia argue that the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for the steps it has taken.
U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the U.N. Security Council on Thursday: “The enforcement of Security Council sanctions must proceed vigorously until denuclearization is complete, final and verifiable.”
The Security Council has unanimously tightened sanctions against North Korea since 2006 in an attempt to strangle funding for North Korea’s nuclear and ballistic missile programs.
Pompeo met Ri on the sidelines of the UN General Assembly and later said he would visit Pyongyang again next month to prepare for a second summit.
Pompeo has visited North Korea three times this year, but the last visit did not go well.
He left Pyongyang in July saying progress had been made, though North Korea later denounced him for "making gangster demands.
At a meeting with Moon this month, North Korea pledged to dismantle a missile facility and also a nuclear complex if the United States “takes corresponding action.”
Pompeo said Kim had told him that the “corresponding measures” they sought were Trump’s security guarantees in Singapore, as well as initiatives to normalize relations with Washington.
Harvard students take a course that teaches them how to get enough rest.
A new course at Harvard University this year has put all its students to sleep more, in an initiative to combat the sexist culture of studying in caffeine-soaked “directs.”
One professor concluded that students at this university at the top of the world rankings often had no idea about the most basic concepts about caring for themselves.
Charles Czeisler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and an expert at Brigham and Women’s Hospital, was the author of the course, which he believes to be the first of its kind in the United States.
The inspiration for the course came after giving a lecture on the impact of sleep deprivation on learning.
"In the end, a girl came to me and said, 'Why are you just telling me this in the last year of the course?'
She said no one had ever mentioned the importance of sleep to her, which surprised me,” she told The Telegraph.
The course, first taught this year, explains to students the essential concepts about how good sleep habits contribute positively to academic and athletic performance, as well as to the improvement of overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university’s health services, said the institution decided to introduce the course after concluding that some students suffered from severe sleep deprivation during the week.
The one-hour course includes a number of interactive tasks.
In one section there is an image of a dormitory where students click on coffee mugs, curtains, shoes and books to be informed about the effects of caffeine and light, and about how athletic performance is influenced by sleep deficiency, and the importance of a routine to collect to bed.
In another section, participants are informed about how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risks of stroke, depression, and cancer.
Then, a campus map, with interactive icons, encourages participants to think about their daily routines.
“We know it won’t change the behavior of students instantly.
However, we believe they have a right to know, as we all have a right to know the health effects of the smoking option,” added Professor Czeisler.
The culture of pride in “doing direct” still exists, he said, adding that modern technology and increasing pressure on students makes this a growing problem.
Ensuring that we get enough and quality sleep should be a “secret weapon” for students to combat stress, exhaustion and anxiety, he said, and even to avoid getting fat, as sleep deprivation puts the brain into starvation mode, making them constantly hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian student of physical biology and chemistry, helped Professor Czeisler design the course after attending one of his classes last year at Harvard.
The course opened his eyes and inspired him to encourage the creation of a campus-wide course, he said.
The next step, according to their expectations, is to ask all postgraduate students to attend a similar study program before entering the competitive institution.
Professor Czeisler advised students to consider using an alarm when going to bed, as well as when waking up, and to be aware of the harmful effects of the “blue light” emitted by electronic screens and LED lighting, which can deregulate the circadian rhythm and lead to problems falling asleep.
