Almanac: the inventor of the Geiger counter
And now a page from our Almanac "Sunday Morning": On September 30, 1882, it is today 136 years old and continues to tell ...the future physicist Johannes Wilhelm "Hans" Geiger was born in Germany.
Geiger developed a method for detecting and measuring radioactivity, an invention that eventually led to the device known as the Geiger counter.
A fundamental piece of science since then, the accountant Geiger has also become a central element of pop culture, as in the 1950 film "Bells of Coronado" in which the unlikely cowboy scientists Roy Rogers and Dale Evans participated:
Man: "What the hell is that?"
Rogers: "It's a Geiger counter, used to locate radioactive minerals like a uranium.
When we put these headphones on, we can even hear the effects of the atoms released by radioactivity on the minerals.”
Evans: "Look, it's really cracking now!"
"Hans" Geiger died in 1945, just days before his 63rd birthday.
But the invention to which he gave the name still endures.
New Cancer Vaccine Teaches Your Immune System to “See” Harmful Cells
New Cancer Vaccine Teaches the Immune System to “See” Harmful Cells and Kill Them
The vaccine teaches the immune system to recognize harmful cells as part of treatment
The method involves the extraction of immune cells from a patient and their alteration in the laboratory.
These cells, which can “see” a protein common to many cancers, are then injected back into the body.
An experimental vaccine is producing promising results in patients with a range of cancers.
A woman treated with the vaccine, which teaches the immune system to recognize harmful cells, has seen her ovarian cancer disappear for more than 18 months.
The method involves the extraction of immune cells from a patient and their modification in the laboratory so that they can "see" a protein common to many cancers, called HER2. These cells are then again injected into the body.
Professor Jay Berzofsky of the U.S. National Cancer Institute in Bethesda, Maryland, said: “Our results suggest that we have a very promising vaccine.”
HER2 “controls the growth of various types of cancer,” including those of the breast, ovary, lungs and also colorectals, Professor Berzofsky explained.
A similar approach to removing immune cells from patients and “teaching” them to attack cancer cells worked in the treatment of one type of leukemia.
