National Trust spies on the secret life of bats
Further investigations are underway at a property in the Scottish Highlands to reveal how bats use the landscape to hunt for food.
The results are expected to shed some light on the behavior of these singular flying mammals and help guide conservation activities in the future.
The study, conducted by scientists from the National Trust for Scotland, will follow common bats and fruit, as well as long-eared chestnuts and Daubenton bats in the Inverewe Gardens in Wester Ross.
Special recorders will be placed in key locations scattered throughout the property to follow bat activities throughout the season.
Mobile studies will also be carried out by NTS staff and volunteers with portable detectors.
Expert analysis of all recordings will assess the frequency of bat calls and what each species is doing.
A habitat map will then be produced to create a detailed picture of their behaviors at the territorial scale.
Rob Dewar, NTS’s conservation adviser, hopes the results will reveal which areas of habitat are most important to bats and how they are used by each of the species.
This information will help determine the benefits of habitat management work, such as grassland creation, as well as how best to maintain forests for bats and associated species.
Bat populations in Scotland and throughout the UK have declined considerably over the past century.
These animals are threatened by construction and development work that affects dormitories and makes habitat scarce.
Wind turbines and lightning also pose a threat, along with fly-killing papers and some chemical treatments of building materials, in addition to attacks by domestic cats.
In fact, bats are not blind.
However, given their nocturnal hunting habits, their ears are more useful than their eyes when it comes to catching prey.
They use a sophisticated echo locating technique to identify insects and obstacles in their flight path.
The NTS, responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land throughout the region, takes bats very seriously.
The organization has ten trained specialists who regularly carry out studies, inspections of dormitories and sometimes rescues.
It also created the first reserve in Scotland dedicated exclusively to bats, on the Threave estate in Dumfries and Galloway, which is home to eight of the ten species of Scottish bats.
The property’s director, David Thompson, says it’s the ideal territory for them.
“Here in Threave we have an excellent area for bats,” he said.
“We have the old buildings, a lot of old trees and all this good habitat.
However, there’s still a lot about bats we don’t know about, so the work we’ve done here and at the other properties will help us know more about what they need to flourish.”
He stressed the importance of checking for bats before carrying out maintenance on the properties, as the unintentional destruction of only one maternity dorm can lead to the death of up to 400 females and young animals, which could eradicate the entire local population.
Bats are a protected species and it is illegal to kill them, harass them, disturb them or destroy their dormitories.
Elisabeth Ferrell, the Scottish head of the Bat Conservation Trust, encouraged the public to participate to help.
“We still have a lot to learn about our bats, and for many of our species, we just don’t know how their populations are avenging.”
