Up-to-date information on the Red Tide: concentrations decrease in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
According to new information from the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission, there has been a decrease in concentrations of red tide in some areas of Tampa Bay.
The FWC reported that conditions of lower spot proliferation have been identified in the Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier counties areas, suggesting a decrease in concentrations.
The Red Tide patch stretches about 201 km along the coast, from Pinellas County in the north to Lee County in the south.
Spots can be found about 16 km off the coast of Hillsborough County, but in fewer areas than last week.
The Red Tide was also spotted in Pasco County.
Last week, there were average concentrations off the coast of Pinella County, low to high concentrations off the coast of Hillsborough County, background to high concentrations in Manatee County, background to high concentrations off the coast of Sarasota County, background to medium concentrations in Charlotte County, background to high concentrations off the coast of Collier County, and background to low concentrations off the coast of Le Collier County.
There continue to be reports of respiratory irritations in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier counties.
Last week, there were no reports of respiratory irritations in northwest Florida.
